 important prose writings, including letters and key statements about his art. Edited and annotated by acclaimed Burns biographer Robert Crawford and textual expert Christopher MacLachlan, the book also includes a substantial introduction that puts the poet in biographical, historical, and cultural context.The Best Laid Schemes demonstrates like no other collection why Burns is considered one of the world's greatest poets of love and democracy-and why he continues to entertain, move, and intrigue readers two and a half centuries after his birth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOETRY / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAddress to Edinburgh.  aAfton Water.  aAuld Lang Syne.  aBeelzebub, Address of.  aBrose and Butter.  aCharlie He's my Darling.  aComin thro' the Rye.  aDavie, Second Epistle to.  aDeil, Address to the.  aDumfries Volunteers, The.  aEdinburgh, Address to.  aEpistle to Davie, A Brother Poet.  aEpistle to Dr Blacklock.  aFergusson, Lines on.  aFor the Author's Father.  aGreen Grow the Rashes. A Fragment.  aHere is to the king, Sir.  aHeron Ballads I.  aHighland Mary.  aHoly Willie's Prayer.  aI Courted a Lassie.  aI Love My Jean.  aInscribed around Fergusson's Portrait.  aJohn Anderson my Jo.  aJolly Beggars, The.  aLetter to Agnes McLehose.  aLines on Fergusson.  aLogie o' Buchan.  aMary Morison.  aMy Father was a Farmer.  aMy Heart's in the Highlands.  aNorthern Lass, The.  aO Leave Novels.  aOn a Noisy Polemic.  aRed Red Rose, A.  aRights of Woman, The.  aRobin Shure in Hairst.  aScots, Wha Hae.  aSecond Epistle to Davie.  aSelkirk Grace, The.  aTam Glen.  aTam Lin.  aThere was a Lad.  aTo Ruin.  aTo a Haggis.  aTo a Mouse.  aTrogger, The.  aTwa Dogs, A Tale, The.  aVision, The.  aWhy S